item.title: [TINKERPOP-2877] The incorrect result caused by long integer overflows
item.description:
Gremlin1: g.V().both().both().both().both().both().both().values('prop9').sum()
Result1: -5308416236269507008
Gremlin2: g.V().both().both().both().both().both().both().has('prop2').values('prop9').sum()
Result2: 7564934332510933333
Gremlin3: g.V().both().both().both().both().both().both().hasNot('prop2').values('prop9').sum()
Result3: -8222751935482731416

We execute the above gremlin queries: Result1 should equal the sum of Result2 and Result3, whereas -5308416236269507008 ≠7564934332510933333 + -8222751935482731416.

The possible reason is that long integer overflows happen in the process. Could you return an exception to notify the user when the overflow occurs, or use BigDecimal during the procedure?

item.summary: The incorrect result caused by long integer overflows

status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.

comments.comment:
thanks for reporting this - not sure what the solution is but that doesn't seem so nice. here's a more simple reproducer:

gremlin> g.inject(Long.MAX_VALUE, 0).sum()
==>9223372036854775807
gremlin> g.inject(Long.MAX_VALUE, 1).sum()
==>-9223372036854775808
gremlin> g.inject(Long.MAX_VALUE, 2).sum()
==>-9223372036854775807
gremlin> g.inject(Long.MAX_VALUE, 3).sum()
==>-9223372036854775806
Many thanks for your valuable response. I also cannot find a very good solution. Perhaps returning an exception to inform the user when this situation occurs could provide some relief.

(From https://github.com/ArcadeData/arcadedb/issues/911#issuecomment-1452096946)

So I guess Gremlin should recognize that a sum it's going to break the Long limit and use BigInteger instead? Not sure if this is something the user should expect, because the result wouldn't a long anymore causing more pain to check what actual Number implementation is returned.

I think there is no easy way to fix it unless you explicitly use BitInteger in gremlin, so you're aware this can happen.

I found a solution that works:

value = graph.gremlin("g.inject(new BigInteger(Long.MAX_VALUE), 1).sum()").execute().nextIfAvailable();
Assertions.assertEquals(BigInteger.valueOf(Long.MAX_VALUE).add(BigInteger.valueOf(1L)), (BigInteger) value.getProperty("result"));

If you explicitly use new BigInteger() in your gremlin, it would work.

I find there is another way to trigger the integer overflow by "count", and I am not sure whether the two issues are caused by the same bug in the code.

 

g.V().repeat(out()).times(10000).count() //Repeat with large number of times and count it

vkagamlyk opened a new pull request, #2315:
URL: https://github.com/apache/tinkerpop/pull/2315

For some integer operations the result is not checked for overflow, which can lead to unexpected results.
For example
```
gremlin> __.inject(Long.MAX_VALUE,Long.MAX_VALUE,2).sum()
==>0
```

In this PR I added throwing `ArithmeticException` for overflow cases.

More details in https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TINKERPOP-2877
